On Wed, Mar 7, 2012 at 10:37 PM, mike amundsen &lt;mamund@...&gt; wrote:

&gt; **
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Glenn:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt; What about the counter view that each client and server combo is the
&gt; &#39;application&#39;
&gt;
&gt; first, i&#39;m not sure that is a &quot;counter view&quot; of what i said. IOW, how
&gt; does this run &quot;counter&quot; to my POV?
&gt;
&gt; second, the term &quot;application&quot; can be applied lots of ways.
&gt; - a single component running on a singe machine,
&gt; - a group of components running on a single machine
&gt; - a group of machines running components
&gt; - etc.
&gt;
&gt; finally, what is the &quot;end game&quot; here? IOW, why pursue this line of
&gt; convo? what positive things can result?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
Ok so let&#39;s move away from &#39;application&#39; and talk about a &#39;system&#39;..
 client behaviour has a direct impact on the nature of interactions in your
system and therefore the extents to which it can evolve. So if your clients
consume your service in a way &quot;that hardcodes URIs and workflow and ignores
the affordance details I supply from the service&quot;, this will absolutely
have an impact on the &quot;REST-itude&quot; of your system since it is an emergence
of interaction in your system which directly violates the hypertext
constraint.

As a service provider, you can govern your clients through deliberate
designs that constrain their behaviour and that will help ensure they &#39;do
the right thing&#39; - if you don&#39;t manage to do this and your clients do the
wrong thing then I think that does diminish the quality of your effort.

Cheers,
Mike

